51:47.240 --> 51:51.500
So it's really something that fluctuates for me.

51:51.500 --> 51:53.800
But I think I'm always going to be curious.

51:54.000 --> 51:58.120
I'm always going to be following it, whether or not I believe it.

51:58.180 --> 51:59.760
I just think it's all fascinating.

52:00.000 --> 52:03.020
Especially because it's all playing out on TV in Washington.

52:03.500 --> 52:06.000
And we're having congressional hearings about it.

52:06.180 --> 52:06.640
It's crazy.

52:07.580 --> 52:10.300
What got you into it to begin with?

52:11.240 --> 52:14.200
Well, I mean, I've always been into sci-fi.

52:14.400 --> 52:17.980
I've always been into the idea of aliens and stuff.

52:17.980 --> 52:19.060
So I've never seen anything.

52:19.840 --> 52:26.540
And if I do, I probably can't say anything because I'm like the least credible person out there.

52:27.320 --> 52:29.340
Because he's like, yeah, of course Fly Lotus saw that.

52:30.020 --> 52:31.240
Of course he did.

52:31.740 --> 52:33.760
But no, I haven't seen anything.

52:33.760 --> 52:39.280
But I've always felt that there is more out there.

52:40.420 --> 52:49.020
And I've made a film about a couple of films with alien themes.

52:49.440 --> 52:49.780
A few, yeah.

52:49.900 --> 52:50.120
Yeah.

52:50.120 --> 53:03.280
And I think when I was filming Ash, when we were filming that movie, Aaron Pohl told me about David Grush.

53:03.420 --> 53:03.780
Mm-hmm.

53:04.340 --> 53:08.480
Because that video, the videos of him with Ross Colhart has just come out.

53:08.600 --> 53:08.860
Mm-hmm.

53:08.860 --> 53:13.140
And I saw that on my timeline, but I was just kind of like, I don't know, I'll go through it.

53:13.140 --> 53:15.120
But then he was like, yo, man, you got to check him out.

53:15.180 --> 53:16.300
I believe this guy.

53:16.780 --> 53:20.960
And Aaron, I wouldn't have guessed that he was like really into the topic.

53:21.880 --> 53:27.080
But, you know, I watched it and then it kind of took me down the rabbit hole, I guess.

53:27.260 --> 53:27.480
Yeah.

53:28.580 --> 53:31.280
But Aaron, you know, he's wild.

53:31.440 --> 53:32.860
He talked to Bob Lazar.

53:33.220 --> 53:34.220
He talked to Bob Lazar?

53:34.520 --> 53:34.860
Yeah, he talked to Bob Lazar.

53:34.860 --> 53:35.380
Aaron Pohl?

53:35.380 --> 53:36.860
Aaron Pohl talked to Bob Lazar.

53:36.860 --> 53:39.980
Yeah, and like they were like writing messages to each other.

53:40.280 --> 53:40.400
No way.

53:40.540 --> 53:41.000
I know.

53:41.240 --> 53:43.140
I'd love to be a fly on the wall for that.

53:43.200 --> 53:43.700
I know.

53:43.840 --> 53:44.120
I know.

53:44.180 --> 53:45.220
You got to get him on the show.

53:45.260 --> 53:46.080
I would love to.

53:46.260 --> 53:49.980
Well, I guess Breaking Bad is kind of a Vegas-y show.

53:50.120 --> 53:52.500
Like I don't, I'm trying to think where that would even have occurred.

53:52.500 --> 53:57.240
I don't know how the connection is made, but like he's a fascinating cat.

53:57.380 --> 53:57.700
Whoa.

53:58.300 --> 53:58.500
Yeah.

53:58.840 --> 54:00.280
Well, Ash was amazing, man.

54:00.380 --> 54:00.800
I loved it.

54:00.820 --> 54:03.900
And this set kind of reminds me, I was texting you, I was like.

54:04.600 --> 54:05.640
This is not a set.

54:05.720 --> 54:06.540
We're in a spaceship.

54:06.860 --> 54:09.120
We're in an actual spaceship.

54:09.320 --> 54:09.760
Yeah, yeah.

54:09.760 --> 54:11.220
And you have the coolest shirt.

54:11.500 --> 54:11.740
Oh.

54:11.820 --> 54:12.920
If you want to show it to the camera.

54:13.600 --> 54:19.740
We got Lockheed Martin, Aurora, antimatter, matter reaction, antigravity.

54:20.040 --> 54:20.800
It's crazy, man.

54:20.800 --> 54:21.760
I have another one too.

54:21.920 --> 54:24.960
Like the Lockheed Martin reverse engineering program.

54:25.280 --> 54:25.900
No way.

54:26.040 --> 54:26.300
Yeah.

54:26.400 --> 54:27.240
It's ridiculous.

54:27.660 --> 54:28.780
I think it's fascinating.

54:29.180 --> 54:34.580
That whole thing, that whole side of it has just been like, just super interesting to me.

54:34.580 --> 54:35.660
It's so interesting.

54:35.780 --> 54:40.840
The reverse engineering stuff and how much of that, because there's definitely weird deception

54:40.840 --> 54:44.360
and like, you know, psyops going on with aerospace.

54:44.780 --> 54:46.480
And then how much of it is real?

54:46.520 --> 54:49.200
Because there's a lot of evidence that there's something there as well.

54:49.320 --> 54:49.600
Yeah.

54:49.600 --> 54:50.400
So it's fascinating.

54:50.580 --> 54:53.960
But it's funny that you said like, of course, Fly Low is seen in Alien.

54:54.120 --> 54:54.240
Yeah.

54:54.380 --> 54:58.680
When I first heard your music, I was like, this dude's in Alien.

54:59.320 --> 55:06.060
Because I was super into like Dilla and Pete Rock and DJ Premier, all these like 90s hip hop producers.

55:06.060 --> 55:16.180
And then you came on the scene and I think it might've been around your album, Cosmogramma or Los Angeles, like 08, you know, 2010 era.

55:17.320 --> 55:21.580
And I just, I saw you play actually with Thundercat in New York.

55:22.540 --> 55:28.380
And I remember, cause like Dilla would mess people up because his stuff wasn't quantized.

55:28.380 --> 55:32.260
And then I remember hearing your stuff and I was like, this guy's on another planet.

55:32.860 --> 55:33.960
Like, this is crazy.

55:34.320 --> 55:36.240
Hey, well, you know, they made it okay.

55:36.420 --> 55:38.260
They made it okay for us to go there.

55:38.400 --> 55:38.660
Yeah.

55:39.800 --> 55:40.200
So.

55:40.560 --> 55:41.960
Well, you took it to the next level.

55:42.100 --> 55:44.400
Hey, well, hey, doing my part, doing my part.

55:45.020 --> 55:45.240
Yeah.

55:45.340 --> 55:54.580
But, you know, it's, it's funny though, because I got, you know, just like everybody else, probably I got a lot of flack in the beginning for doing my thing.

55:54.580 --> 56:01.340
You know, and being, being that person, like I keep bringing this up lately because it's so bizarre to people.

56:01.340 --> 56:11.480
But like back when I was first getting on and the scene, like around like what, 2004, um, I get a lot of shit.

56:11.700 --> 56:12.300
Can I say shit?

56:12.400 --> 56:12.840
I'm a person.

56:12.840 --> 56:13.340
Yeah, you can say shit.

56:13.540 --> 56:14.400
Oh yeah, yeah.

56:14.580 --> 56:15.520
As much as you want.

56:15.920 --> 56:19.080
I used to get a lot of shit for using a computer to make music.

56:19.360 --> 56:19.720
Really?

56:19.940 --> 56:21.160
Back in that, back in the day.

56:21.180 --> 56:22.160
Instead of an MPC.

56:22.160 --> 56:28.360
Yeah, you had to have an MPC, you know, or, or SP or something like that, or else you wasn't making hip hop.

56:28.460 --> 56:31.180
You was making techno or computer music or whatever.

56:31.300 --> 56:37.000
They was just like, there's no way, there's no way you can, you ain't, there ain't no swing in that computer.

56:37.160 --> 56:38.220
You can't swing with that.

56:38.480 --> 56:45.060
So it made me more determined to, to like really get in there and get the sounds and to try different stuff.

56:45.060 --> 56:56.280
And, and I actually was, was really encouraged earlier on in my development to, you know, just to do the other thing, just to try and go in different directions.

56:56.280 --> 57:06.020
And so I owe a lot to the people around me really who supported me to just like not do, not to do what everyone else was doing at the time.

57:06.160 --> 57:12.420
Well, you come from maybe the most kind of interesting musical family I could think of.

57:12.840 --> 57:16.360
Alice Coltrane is your, what is your great aunt?

57:16.460 --> 57:16.900
Is that right?

57:16.900 --> 57:23.720
And then, uh, Marilyn McLeod is your grandmother and she, she wrote love hangover.

57:23.720 --> 57:32.120
And she also wrote, uh, I get hot or I get high as the styles P, um, uh, uh, Swiss beats sample.

57:32.420 --> 57:33.940
Uh, but it's, it's no, it's, it is.

57:34.020 --> 57:34.740
I get high too.

57:34.740 --> 57:35.020
Right.

57:35.120 --> 57:35.380
Yeah.

57:35.380 --> 57:36.560
The original free to paint.

57:36.580 --> 57:36.820
Yeah.

57:36.880 --> 57:37.760
She wrote that as well.

57:37.940 --> 57:43.200
So you just come from amazing, you know, family when it comes to this stuff.

57:43.200 --> 57:45.120
They still was looking at me like I was crazy though.

57:45.120 --> 57:48.780
And I was like, why does shit sound like some garbage, hitting on some garbage cans?

57:48.940 --> 57:50.780
You know, like why, what is, what is this?

57:51.220 --> 57:53.640
And, uh, I was like, but you guys are crazy too.

57:53.760 --> 57:54.540
What are you talking about?

57:55.180 --> 57:57.600
Um, but yeah, I had to find, find my way.

57:57.860 --> 57:59.620
Just like, um, just like we all do.

57:59.760 --> 58:00.300
It is true.

58:00.380 --> 58:03.800
Your, your drums, I think set you apart.

58:04.020 --> 58:11.520
So it's like that plus the crazy synths, like the, like sounded like it was like you, you leaned into the computer thing.

58:11.520 --> 58:11.800
Yeah.

58:12.000 --> 58:12.180
Yeah.

58:12.180 --> 58:18.040
And it was like that plus the drums, which, you know, it was like, yeah, it was like garbage, like back alley, like crazy.

58:18.140 --> 58:20.040
And it was like, oh my God, this is crazy.

58:20.220 --> 58:20.480
Yeah.

58:20.560 --> 58:20.800
Yeah.

58:21.000 --> 58:23.460
Well, yeah, just, just went for it, man.

58:23.500 --> 58:24.480
Just went for it.

58:24.600 --> 58:27.840
Um, a lot of support from, from my grandmother though.

58:28.080 --> 58:32.320
Um, she was the first person to put a machine in my hands.

58:32.320 --> 58:39.420
You know, she had was the, the six, six Oh six, the T TV six Oh six or something like that.

58:39.460 --> 58:45.840
Like one of them drum machines with like, you know, those weird analog sounds and stuff in there.

58:45.840 --> 58:48.220
And she was just like, here, take it.

58:48.260 --> 58:50.920
I was just making drum beats and stuff when I was really young.

58:50.920 --> 58:53.120
And that was kind of what, what set me up.

58:53.120 --> 59:02.520
And then just being around different family, like my cousin, he was making music on a Mac to CI, like old, old Mac.

59:02.520 --> 59:05.600
Like back when that was like super foreign to record on.

59:05.900 --> 59:09.560
And, um, you know, I was watching him while I'm playing Sonic the Hedgehog.

59:09.560 --> 59:12.980
Like he's like making stuff that sounded like Prince and stuff.

59:12.980 --> 59:19.620
And like, I was just always surrounded by music and always surrounded by people trying to make stuff.

59:19.940 --> 59:20.480
That makes sense.

59:20.540 --> 59:21.740
You played Sonic the Hedgehog.

59:21.800 --> 59:25.540
Cause it, I feel like it's that Sega, like wave racer vibe.

59:25.540 --> 59:26.500
Oh man, no doubt.

59:26.940 --> 59:29.280
And those loops, man, they still in my head, man.

59:29.400 --> 59:32.180
You know, I still, I still be sampling Sonic too.

59:34.040 --> 59:35.140
Still to this day.

59:35.220 --> 59:36.060
That's awesome.

59:36.180 --> 59:36.420
Yeah.

59:36.580 --> 59:36.880
Yeah.

59:36.880 --> 59:41.260
So was Alice an inspiration for you early on?

59:41.260 --> 59:52.180
My aunt Alice was such an inspiration, but I feel like my appreciation for her and her music grew, grew over time.

59:52.300 --> 01:00:00.700
You know, like when I was, I feel like kind of in high school, all the stuff started to make more sense to me and I was really starting to see it.

01:00:00.700 --> 01:00:13.140
But then when I went to college and really started like vibing there and like, you know, trying mushrooms and stuff and like, you know, leaving my brain and stuff, I'm like, oh, I get it for real now.

01:00:13.140 --> 01:00:15.020
You know, it was really starting to make sense.

01:00:15.480 --> 01:00:18.600
And, um, and I had just the deepest appreciation for it.

01:00:18.600 --> 01:00:26.100
But, you know, I'm still to this day, like, I feel like every other year I'll go back and listen to music that she made and just be like, whoa, what was she doing?

01:00:26.400 --> 01:00:27.120
How did she do that?

01:00:27.220 --> 01:00:28.300
Why, why did she do that?

01:00:28.700 --> 01:00:29.640
That was a weird choice.

01:00:29.860 --> 01:00:30.480
Great choice.

01:00:30.660 --> 01:00:35.120
But, you know, like, I'm still, still picking it apart after all these years.

01:00:35.360 --> 01:00:37.560
And you said she never saw her practice.

01:00:37.620 --> 01:00:38.660
I never saw her practice.

01:00:38.920 --> 01:00:39.500
That's crazy.

01:00:39.500 --> 01:00:44.360
Never in my, in my entire, and I, you know, she was like the Coltrane side.

01:00:44.360 --> 01:00:47.900
The, they're like the closest family to me in LA.

01:00:48.780 --> 01:00:50.820
And, um, so I spent a lot of time over there.

01:00:50.900 --> 01:00:54.080
I, you know, I went to this, to the school right by their house.

01:00:54.160 --> 01:00:57.300
So I walked from school to hang out over there all the time.

01:00:57.300 --> 01:00:59.860
And, you know, I would see them very often.

01:01:00.000 --> 01:01:01.860
I never saw her practice.

01:01:02.140 --> 01:01:02.400
Never.

01:01:02.640 --> 01:01:13.820
And, um, I remember when I, one time when I was like, maybe like 10, 11 years old, I went over to the house and she had a beautiful piano, beautiful grand Steinway piano.

01:01:14.360 --> 01:01:18.460
Um, surrounded by, you know, her harp and all these amazing instruments.

01:01:18.580 --> 01:01:20.600
I went in there and I was like, hey, can I go play your piano?

01:01:20.820 --> 01:01:21.060
Yeah.

01:01:21.620 --> 01:01:23.780
She was like, well, are you going to play it?

01:01:25.680 --> 01:01:28.940
I was like, I don't, I don't know, actually.

01:01:29.420 --> 01:01:31.080
What do you think she meant by that?

01:01:31.080 --> 01:01:32.760
She meant, am I going to get down, dude?

01:01:32.860 --> 01:01:35.000
Like, don't mess around, you know?

01:01:35.000 --> 01:01:37.460
Like, don't go in there, like, messing around on my piano.

01:01:37.580 --> 01:01:38.720
You're going to go in there and play it.

01:01:39.060 --> 01:01:41.740
You can go play it, but you better play.

01:01:41.740 --> 01:01:45.660
So I was like, I took that like, so I didn't do it.

01:01:45.880 --> 01:01:47.880
I never, I never touched that thing ever.

01:01:48.160 --> 01:01:52.060
And she was very kind of spiritually tapped in as well, right?

01:01:52.060 --> 01:01:54.800
Oh man, yeah, she was the most, she was the most tapped in.

01:01:55.060 --> 01:02:01.040
I would say, yeah, there was a lot of influence, but I guess it would be more non-denominational leaning.

01:02:01.040 --> 01:02:04.800
But, but yeah, a lot of, a lot of influence there.

01:02:05.160 --> 01:02:05.500
Definitely.

01:02:05.980 --> 01:02:06.200
Yeah.

01:02:06.600 --> 01:02:06.820
Yeah.

01:02:06.820 --> 01:02:07.520
She's amazing.

01:02:07.620 --> 01:02:12.040
I mean, just hearing, what's it, I think it was Turiya and Ramakrishna.

01:02:12.420 --> 01:02:12.660
Yeah.

01:02:12.760 --> 01:02:13.720
Yeah, yeah, yeah, yeah, yeah.

01:02:13.780 --> 01:02:16.840
It's like that old blues kind of vibe.

01:02:17.040 --> 01:02:18.940
And it's just so beautiful.

01:02:19.000 --> 01:02:20.600
It's like ethereal and beautiful.

01:02:20.860 --> 01:02:22.040
And you're like, where is this coming from?

01:02:22.080 --> 01:02:22.580
It's amazing.

01:02:22.580 --> 01:02:30.900
It's wild because it can always be, you can always hear the blues and then it just goes to some other, just crazy places.

01:02:31.320 --> 01:02:42.440
And I remember being with her in, in Paris once she, she had me come with her and, and Ravi, they play the show in Paris toward the end of her life.

01:02:42.700 --> 01:02:49.880
And, um, I just remember just hearing her, you know, she was like a, she was like Yoda.

01:02:49.880 --> 01:02:58.200
You know, she was like a Yoda type person where she was like real, she was really tiny and, you know, moved very slowly, very gentle with everything.

01:02:58.720 --> 01:03:05.260
But, you know, she just, when she went on that piano, boom, was busting out all crazy, you know, like, who is this person?

01:03:05.420 --> 01:03:09.520
And it was like, even, even Rodney, her son, she was like, whoa, what is going on?

01:03:09.600 --> 01:03:09.820
You know?

01:03:09.880 --> 01:03:14.300
So like, she just had, she was tapped in for sure to the, to the source.

01:03:15.040 --> 01:03:17.800
Well, John was tapped in as well.

01:03:17.800 --> 01:03:23.900
I mean, I think he might be like at least top three, maybe favorite jazz musician of all time.

01:03:24.180 --> 01:03:26.340
Are you a fan of his as well?

01:03:26.580 --> 01:03:26.600
Absolutely.

01:03:26.780 --> 01:03:27.140
Absolutely.

01:03:27.440 --> 01:03:30.760
And, and I think, I think I was a fan of his first.

01:03:31.360 --> 01:03:41.100
And it was, it's funny because when I was growing up and I would, people would want to talk to my aunt and be around people who want to talk to her.

01:03:41.160 --> 01:03:43.200
I always want to talk to her about John Coltrane.

01:03:43.200 --> 01:03:47.160
All I want to talk to her about is like, what was it like being around John Coltrane?

01:03:47.240 --> 01:03:47.820
What was he like?

01:03:47.900 --> 01:03:48.460
What was he like?

01:03:48.620 --> 01:03:51.200
And she would always answer very humbly.

01:03:51.480 --> 01:03:56.020
And, you know, and then now it's like everyone wants to talk about Alice Coltrane.

01:03:56.020 --> 01:04:00.340
And it's, it's really awesome to see that, just to see the turn happen.

01:04:00.620 --> 01:04:10.980
But I, I do wish she, that she was here to, to see her, her influence, um, in the way, because I feel like now I'm hearing way more about her than him.

01:04:11.200 --> 01:04:16.800
Even though he's, you know, I go to sushi restaurant, it's always John Coltrane playing, you know what I'm saying?

01:04:16.800 --> 01:04:23.660
But like, I just feel like the, the young, the young folks around are, are really vibing on our music right now.

01:04:23.740 --> 01:04:24.820
And it's really cool to see.

01:04:25.040 --> 01:04:25.440
Absolutely.

01:04:25.780 --> 01:04:29.680
Well, she really, I think just pushed the envelope and experimented.

01:04:29.740 --> 01:04:31.540
Obviously he was amazing too.

01:04:31.780 --> 01:04:31.820
Yeah.

01:04:32.400 --> 01:04:33.920
Um, that is cool to see.

01:04:33.940 --> 01:04:39.780
And it's interesting how music kind of like your UFO interest ebbs and flows and changes.

01:04:39.780 --> 01:04:44.780
And how do you feel like, do you feel like it's in an interesting place right now?

01:04:44.840 --> 01:04:46.220
Do you feel like it's in a weird place?

01:04:46.400 --> 01:04:53.240
Like what music, music in general, is that even a, is that even a question you can ask or is it just, it is what it is?

01:04:53.240 --> 01:05:01.720
You know, as far as the industry and all that stuff, I, I can separate it and think about it in terms of like the actual music itself.

01:05:01.720 --> 01:05:03.660
And there's always some good stuff going on.

01:05:03.660 --> 01:05:03.940
Always.

01:05:04.120 --> 01:05:04.400
Always.

01:05:04.560 --> 01:05:05.300
Always interesting.

01:05:05.660 --> 01:05:06.480
You just got to look for it.

01:05:06.560 --> 01:05:06.780
Yeah.

01:05:06.960 --> 01:05:07.980
You got to seek it out.

01:05:07.980 --> 01:05:16.000
But, you know, if you're only going to listen to what the charts are telling you, then you're probably going to be thinking it's, it's all the same.

01:05:16.260 --> 01:05:21.740
It's definitely weird that it's now filtered by, is the person a good social media personality?

01:05:22.020 --> 01:05:22.220
Absolutely.

01:05:22.500 --> 01:05:23.180
That's weird to me.

01:05:23.220 --> 01:05:23.660
Absolutely.

01:05:24.020 --> 01:05:30.520
And like the numbers, like people, people even see like, okay, well, they only have certain amount of listeners on Spotify.

01:05:30.760 --> 01:05:32.020
So they're probably not that good.

01:05:32.200 --> 01:05:32.440
Yeah.

01:05:32.780 --> 01:05:34.120
They're probably not that great.

01:05:34.120 --> 01:05:34.440
Yeah.

01:05:34.580 --> 01:05:37.820
They only got like 10,000 listeners every month.

01:05:37.820 --> 01:05:39.380
So they're probably, eh.

01:05:39.760 --> 01:05:40.100
Right.

01:05:40.220 --> 01:05:43.860
It's this like infinite force ranking of everything.

01:05:44.060 --> 01:05:44.420
Absolutely.

01:05:44.560 --> 01:05:46.200
Everything's a beauty contest.

01:05:46.340 --> 01:05:46.740
Oh, dude.

01:05:46.940 --> 01:05:47.260
Yeah.

01:05:47.360 --> 01:05:56.540
And I feel like in the past 10 years, you know, the, the numbers thing really got into the fandoms of rappers and stuff.

01:05:56.540 --> 01:05:59.260
Like, you know, first week sales and stuff.

01:05:59.440 --> 01:06:03.860
Like people are like, kids are talking about rappers first week sales, like selling what?

01:06:03.940 --> 01:06:05.140
What are people selling anymore?

01:06:05.260 --> 01:06:06.680
Like y'all buying records and stuff?

01:06:06.840 --> 01:06:15.240
Like what is, what is, it's just, it's super weird that that's actually part of the conversation in terms of like, is something good or interesting?

01:06:15.240 --> 01:06:17.040
